Title: Electronic Warfare (EW) / Counter-Unmanned Aircraft Systems (C-UAS)                                                                     -       22.000         61.108
Description: Technology maturation efforts will prototype a family of key components and systems for EW and C-UAS, scaling
from small form factor applications, such as soldier borne to platform based and other long-range applications. Commonality (such
as hardware, algorithms, and techniques) and modular open systems approach (MOSA) across the family of systems provides the
ability to adapt to rapidly evolving operational environments.

FY 2026 Plans:
Evaluated key components, architectures and systems for EW scaling from small form factor applications for platform based
applications. Commonality (such as hardware, algorithms, and techniques) across the family of systems were analyzed and
developed that provides the ability to adapt to rapidly evolving operational environments. Conducted a preliminary design review,
integrated a proximity sensor and power into a munition fuze. Performed software and hardware updates to fire control devices,
conducted fuze and fire control benchtop and ballistic engineering tests.
FY 2027 Plans:
This effort will support four critical initiatives in EW and C-UAS:

1. Multi-Mode Direct Fire Systems to Counter sUAS Threats: Will focus on the continued maturation, integration, and operational
testing of a prototype system that integrates the Common Remotely Operated Weapon Station (CROWS) with a MK19 grenade
launcher and a '3-in-1' 40mm airburst munition. These activities will advance the development of scalable, affordable targeting
capabilities to address the growing threat of small unmanned aerial systems (sUAS). By closing this critical capability gap, the
Army will enhance its ability to protect maneuver forces and ensure mission success in contested environments.

2. Integrated Counter-sUAS Systems for Maneuver and Soldier Echelons: Will focus on the integration, maturation, and
operational demonstration of advanced counter-sUAS systems designed to enhance capabilities for maneuver formations and
dismounted forces. These systems will incorporate innovative component technologies and lessons learned from previous
exercises to ensure adaptability and effectiveness in addressing emerging threats. By advancing these integrated solutions, the
Army will reduce risk and strengthen operational capabilities in contested environments, supporting key priorities in critical areas
of responsibility.

3. Low-Cost Electronic Warfare Systems for Attritable and Expendable Payloads: Will prototype the integration of a family of low-
cost EW systems leveraging commercial hardware, algorithms, and techniques. Further, the funding supports relevant testing
and range time to demonstrate operational utility of the family of prototype solutions. These systems will reduce payload costs

